{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13584"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.83,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6195"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29784"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after experiencing sudden onset chest pain and difficulty breathing while gardening at home. Her symptoms began shortly after she received distressing news that her brother unexpectedly passed away. She has a medical history of controlled hypertension and was recently diagnosed with hyperlipidemia. She is a non-smoker, does not consume alcohol, and has no history of drug use. On examination, her temperature is 37.0\u00b0C, pulse is 102/min, respirations are 20/min, and blood pressure is 158/90 mm Hg. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows transient ST elevation in leads V2\u2013V4, which was not present in an ECG taken during a routine check-up one month ago. Her troponin level is 1200 ng/L (reference range: 0-14 ng/L). Urgent cardiac catheterization reveals normal coronary arteries. Echocardiography indicates significant ballooning of the left ventricular apex with hyperkinesis of the basal segments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute myocardial infarction","Pulmonary embolism","Takotsubo cardiomyopathy","Aortic dissection","Coronary artery vasospasm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETakotsubo cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because this patient presents with symptoms of acute chest pain and dyspnoea, accompanied by ECG changes and elevated troponin levels, which are typical initial indicators of an acute myocardial event. However, the clear coronary arteries demonstrated on angiography and the characteristic echocardiographic findings of apical ballooning with basal segment hyperkinesis clinch the diagnosis of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy. This condition, also known as stress cardiomyopathy, is typically triggered by significant emotional or physical stress. It is believed to involve catecholamine-mediated myocardial toxicity, leading to transient regional wall motion abnormalities. These features are distinctive and differentiate it from an acute myocardial infarction, which would show obstructive coronary disease. Clinically, patients may present with signs and symptoms indistinguishable from those of acute coronary syndromes, but the absence of significant coronary artery obstruction and the presence of apical wall motion abnormalities are key diagnostic features. Management primarily involves supportive care and monitoring, with beta-blockers sometimes used to manage symptoms and prevent recurrence. Understanding the transient nature of the ventricular dysfunction is crucial, as the condition usually resolves within days to weeks without causing permanent damage to the myocardium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E (AMI) is a plausible diagnosis given the symptoms and initial ECG and troponin findings. However, the absence of coronary obstruction on angiography rules out AMI in this scenario. AMI would be considered correct if coronary artery blockages were found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E can present with chest pain and shortness of breath and increased troponin, but this patient\u0027s absence of hypoxia and typical ECG changes (like an S1Q3T3 pattern) makes PE less likely. According to the Wells criteria, the patient\u0027s pulse rate over 100 bpm is the only factor present. Other factors such as recent surgery or immobilization, signs of deep vein thrombosis (DVT), haemoptysis, or a history of DVT/PE are not present in this case, making PE an unlikely diagnosis compared to Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, which better explains the specific echocardiographic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E could present with sudden chest pain, increased troponin and might be associated with hypertension, but it typically features very sharp pain, radiating to the back, and can show variations in pulse and blood pressure between limbs; none of which are described in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery vasospasm\u003C/strong\u003E could explain transient ST elevations, elevated troponin and chest pain; however, it does not usually result in the specific type of regional wall motion abnormalities seen in Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, such as apical ballooning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Takotsubo cardiomyopathy should be considered in patients presenting with symptoms mimicking an acute coronary syndrome, particularly when there is recent significant emotional stress and imaging shows typical apical ballooning without coronary artery disease."],"references":["Segan L, Vlachadis Castles A, Fendel K, McFarlane L, Vaddadi G, Amerena J. P812 Takotsubo cardiomyopathy: phenotypic diversity and contemporary management. European Heart Journal. 2019 Oct 1;40(Supplement_1):ehz747-0411.                                                                                  https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehz747.0411"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29784"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29784"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-07T20:06:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-07T20:06:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6195"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44886"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24"